This paper is about improving the training of Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs), which is a popular topic in machine learning research. The paper specifically focuses on the Wasserstein GAN (WGAN) and proposes a new method for enforcing a Lipschitz constraint on the critic. This makes it likely that the paper would be categorized under cs.LG (Machine Learning), which is the most general category for machine learning research. Additionally, since the paper evaluates its proposed method on image datasets such as CIFAR-10 and LSUN bedrooms, it is likely to be categorized under cs.CV (Computer Vision). The paper also mentions language models over discrete data, which suggests it could be categorized under cs.CL (Computation and Language). Finally, since the paper proposes a new method for enforcing a Lipschitz constraint, it could be categorized under cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) or cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), which are both relevant sub-categories for research on GANs and other deep learning models.
